===Etymology 1===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fro|alegier}}, from {{der|en|la|alleviāre}}, present active infinitive of {{m|la|alleviō||lighten}}, from {{m|la|ad}} + {{m|la|levis||light}}. {{doublet|en|alleviate}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|alleg}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[lighten]], [[diminish]].
#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtArthr1}}, Bk.V:
#*: and suffir never your soveraynté to be '''alledged''' with your subjects, nother the soveraygne of your persone and londys.
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.ii:
#*: Hart that is inly hurt, is greatly eased / With hope of thing, that may '''allegge''' his smart{{nb...}}.

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|aleggen}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|xno|aleger}}, the form from {{der|en|fro|esligier}}, from {{der|en|ML.||*exlītigāre|to clear at law}}, from {{der|en|la|ex||out}} + {{m|la|lītigō||sue at law}}, the meaning from Old French {{m|fro|alleguer}}, from Latin {{m|la|allēgāre}}, present active infinitive of {{m|la|allēgō||send, depute; relate, mention, adduce}}, from {{m|la|ad||to}} + {{m|la|lēgō||send}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|alleg}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To [[state]] under [[oath]], to [[plead]].
# {{lb|en|archaic}} To [[cite]] or [[quote]] an author or his work ''for'' or ''against''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[adduce]] (something) as a reason, excuse, support etc.
#* {{RQ:Flr Mntgn Essays}}, I.39:
#*: I will further '''alleage''' a storie{{...}}to make us palpably feele his naturall condition.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make a [[claim]] as [[justification]] or [[proof]]; to make an assertion without proof.
#: {{ux|en|The agency '''alleged''' my credit history had problems.}}

